    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-01-31T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-01-31T04:00:00-05:00" n="614"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d614">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.5431/126: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-01-31T10:00:00+01:00"
                            >January 31, 1935—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 31—6:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>7. Stucki<note n="2" xml:id="d614fn2">Walter Stucki, Chief of the Commercial
                        Division of the Swiss Federal Department of Public Economy.</note> yesterday
                    implied that serious obstacle to reaching a trade agreement with the United
                    States would be the uncertainty of future value of the dollar. He argued that
                    even though the United States granted tariff concessions such benefits would be
                    modified or canceled by further currency devaluation.</p>
                <p>The Department has presumably met this argument before and I should be happy to
                    learn how it has been answered.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
